## Docker Instructions

### Build the Image

```bash
docker build -t churn-app .
```

This will install dependencies, run `train.py` (baking `model.pkl` into the image), and set up the container.

### Run the Container

```bash
docker run -p 8000:8000 churn-app
```

The API is now accessible at `http://localhost:8000/predict`.

---

## AWS EC2 Deployment — Step-by-Step

### Step 1 — Launch an EC2 Instance

1. Log in to [AWS Console](https://console.aws.amazon.com/) → go to **EC2** → click **Launch Instance**
2. Configure:

   | Setting          | Value                                   |
   |------------------|-----------------------------------------|
   | **Name**         | `churn-prediction-server`               |
   | **AMI**          | Amazon Linux 2023 (free tier eligible)  |
   | **Instance type**| `t2.micro` (free tier)                  |
   | **Key pair**     | Create or select an existing key pair   |

3. Under **Network settings**, create or select a security group with these inbound rules:

   | Type      | Port  | Source    | Purpose          |
   |-----------|-------|-----------|------------------|
   | SSH       | 22    | My IP     | Terminal access  |
   | Custom TCP| 8000  | 0.0.0.0/0| API access       |

4. Click **Launch Instance** and wait for it to enter the **Running** state.
5. Note the **Public IPv4 address** (e.g., `3.110.45.123`).

### Step 2 — Connect to the Instance via SSH

```bash
# Make key file read-only (Linux/Mac)
chmod 400 your-key.pem

# Connect
ssh -i your-key.pem ec2-user@<YOUR_PUBLIC_IP>
```

> [!TIP]
> On Windows, use **PuTTY** or the built-in OpenSSH client:
> ```powershell
> ssh -i your-key.pem ec2-user@<YOUR_PUBLIC_IP>
> ```

### Step 3 — Install Docker on the Instance

```bash
# Update packages
sudo yum update -y

# Install Docker
sudo yum install docker -y

# Start Docker and enable auto-start
sudo systemctl start docker
sudo systemctl enable docker

# Add your user to the docker group (avoids needing sudo)
sudo usermod -aG docker ec2-user

# Apply the group change (or log out and back in)
newgrp docker

# Verify Docker is working
docker --version
```

### Step 4 — Upload and Run the Project

**Option A: Clone from GitHub (recommended)**

If you've pushed the project to a GitHub repository:

```bash
# Install git
sudo yum install git -y

# Clone your repo
git clone https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/churn-prediction-system.git
cd churn-prediction-system
```

**Option B: Upload files directly via SCP**

From your local machine:

```bash
scp -i your-key.pem -r ./churn-prediction-system ec2-user@<YOUR_PUBLIC_IP>:~/
```

Then on the EC2 instance:

```bash
cd ~/churn-prediction-system
```

### Step 5 — Build and Run with Docker

```bash
# Build the Docker image
docker build -t churn-app .

# Run the container (detached mode so it keeps running)
docker run -d -p 8000:8000 --name churn-api churn-app
```

### Step 6 — Test the Deployed API

From your **local machine** (replace `<YOUR_PUBLIC_IP>` with your EC2 instance's public IP):

```bash
curl -X POST http://<YOUR_PUBLIC_IP>:8000/predict \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{
    "tenure": 5,
    "monthly_charges": 95.0,
    "total_charges": 475.0,
    "contract": "Month-to-month",
    "internet_service": "Fiber optic",
    "gender": "Male"
  }'
```

**Expected response:**

```json
{
  "prediction": 0,
  "label": "No Churn"
}
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Make sure port **8000** is open in your EC2 security group's inbound rules. If you can't connect, go to **EC2 → Security Groups → Edit Inbound Rules** and add a Custom TCP rule for port 8000.

### Useful Docker Commands on EC2

```bash
docker ps                  # See running containers
docker logs churn-api      # View API logs
docker stop churn-api      # Stop the container
docker rm churn-api        # Remove the container
docker start churn-api     # Restart a stopped container
```

